---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Overtime Calculator",
  description: "Find out exactly how much extra you're earning (and whether you're being underpaid). Uncover the hidden impact of time-and-a-half.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is overtime calculated?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Overtime is typically calculated by multiplying your regular hourly rate by an overtime multiplier (most commonly 1.5, known as time-and-a-half) for all hours worked over the standard limit, which is usually 40 hours in a workweek."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is time and a half?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Time and a half is a standard overtime rate where you are paid your regular hourly rate plus an additional 50% of that rate for every overtime hour worked."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is overtime taxed differently than regular pay?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No, overtime pay is taxed at the same standard income tax rates as your regular wages. However, earning more in a single pay period might cause a larger amount to be withheld for taxes, making it feel like it is taxed at a higher rate."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Who is exempt from overtime pay?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), certain employees are exempt from overtime pay. This typically includes salaried employees acting in executive, administrative, or professional capacities who earn above a specific salary threshold."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can my employer force me to work overtime?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "In most cases, yes. Under federal law, employers generally have the right to require employees to work overtime, provided they are compensated at the proper overtime rate, unless restricted by specific union contracts or state laws."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "Overtime Calculator",
      "description": "Calculate your regular and overtime pay instantly. Understand the mathematics of time-and-a-half and the Fair Labor Standards Act.",
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "SiliconBased"
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<SiteLayout site="firemaths" title="Overtime Calculator | Calculate Time & a Half Pay" description="Find out exactly how much extra you're earning (and whether you're being underpaid). Uncover the hidden impact of time-and-a-half." canonical="https://firemaths.info/overtime-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Overtime Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Calculate your total earnings including regular pay and time-and-a-half overtime.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="hourlyRate">Regular Hourly Rate ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="hourlyRate" min="0" step="0.01" value="20" placeholder="e.g., 20.00" />
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="regularHours">Regular Hours Worked</label>
          <input type="number" id="regularHours" min="0" step="0.5" value="40" placeholder="e.g., 40" />
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="overtimeHours">Overtime Hours Worked</label>
          <input type="number" id="overtimeHours" min="0" step="0.5" value="5" placeholder="e.g., 5" />
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="overtimeMultiplier">Overtime Multiplier</label>
          <select id="overtimeMultiplier">
            <option value="1.5">1.5x (Time and a Half)</option>
            <option value="2.0">2.0x (Double Time)</option>
            <option value="1.0">1.0x (Straight Time)</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="calc-error" class="error-message" style="display: none;"></div>

      <div class="results-grid">
        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Regular Pay</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-regular">$800.00</div>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="result-label">Overtime Pay</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="res-overtime">$150.00</div>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card highlight-card">
          <div class="result-label">Total Gross Pay</div>
          <div class="result-value highlight-val" id="res-total">$950.00</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding Overtime Calculation</h2>
      <p>Working beyond the standard 40-hour workweek often entitles you to premium compensation. This interactive overtime calculator allows you to instantly determine your total gross pay by factoring in your base hourly wage, standard hours, and any overtime hours accumulated at an increased multiplier.</p>

      <h3>The Mathematics of Time-and-a-Half</h3>
      <p>The most common standard for overtime pay in the United States, as mandated by the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), is "time-and-a-half." This implies that for every hour worked beyond 40 hours in a single workweek, a non-exempt employee must be paid at a rate of 1.5 times their regular hourly rate.</p>

      <p>The formula for calculating your pay is straightforward:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Regular Pay</strong> = Regular Hours &times; Hourly Rate</li>
        <li><strong>Overtime Pay</strong> = Overtime Hours &times; Hourly Rate &times; Overtime Multiplier</li>
        <li><strong>Total Gross Pay</strong> = Regular Pay + Overtime Pay</li>
      </ul>

      <p>For example, if you earn $20.00 per hour and work 45 hours in a week, your regular pay covers the first 40 hours ($800.00). The remaining 5 hours are paid at $30.00 per hour ($20.00 &times; 1.5), generating an additional $150.00 in overtime pay. Your total gross earnings for that week would be $950.00.</p>

      <h3>Double Time and Variations</h3>
      <p>While the federal standard is 1.5x, some states and specific union contracts require or stipulate "double time" (a 2.0x multiplier) under certain conditions. In California, for instance, working more than 12 hours in a single workday, or working more than 8 hours on the seventh consecutive day of work in a workweek, triggers double-time pay.</p>

      <h3>Exempt vs. Non-Exempt Employees</h3>
      <p>It is crucial to understand that not all workers are eligible for overtime compensation. The FLSA distinguishes between "exempt" and "non-exempt" employees. Non-exempt employees, typically paid hourly, are entitled to overtime pay. Exempt employees are usually salaried professionals working in administrative, executive, or specialized roles who earn above a specific salary threshold (currently $35,568 per year, though this is subject to legislative changes).</p>

      <p>If you are an hourly worker, you are almost certainly non-exempt. If you are salaried, your eligibility depends heavily on your specific job duties and overall compensation level. If you're a healthcare professional, you may also be interested in our <a href="/creatinine-clearance-calculator">Creatinine Clearance Calculator</a>.</p>

      <h3>Impact on Taxes</h3>
      <p>A common misconception is that overtime pay is taxed at a significantly higher rate than regular pay. From a purely legal standpoint, overtime is considered ordinary income and is taxed at your standard effective tax rate. However, because you earn more money during a pay period featuring overtime, the payroll software may extrapolate that higher earning rate across the entire year. This can cause a higher percentage of your check to be withheld for taxes temporarily. When you file your annual tax return, your total tax liability is calculated based on your total annual income, smoothing out these fluctuations.</p>

      <h3>Why Tracking Your Own Hours Matters</h3>
      <p>Payroll systems are not infallible. Clerical errors, misclassifications, and sometimes intentional wage theft can result in missing overtime pay. By independently tracking your hours and running the calculations yourself using tools like this calculator, you ensure you are being fairly compensated for every hour you dedicate to your employer.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How is overtime calculated?</summary>
        <p>Overtime is typically calculated by multiplying your regular hourly rate by an overtime multiplier (most commonly 1.5, known as time-and-a-half) for all hours worked over the standard limit, which is usually 40 hours in a workweek.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is time and a half?</summary>
        <p>Time and a half is a standard overtime rate where you are paid your regular hourly rate plus an additional 50% of that rate for every overtime hour worked. If you make $10/hour, time-and-a-half is $15/hour.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is overtime taxed differently than regular pay?</summary>
        <p>No, overtime pay is taxed at the same standard income tax rates as your regular wages. However, earning more in a single pay period might cause a larger amount to be withheld for taxes, making it feel like it is taxed at a higher rate.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Who is exempt from overtime pay?</summary>
        <p>Under the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), certain employees are exempt from overtime pay. This typically includes salaried employees acting in executive, administrative, or professional capacities who earn above a specific salary threshold.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can my employer force me to work overtime?</summary>
        <p>In most cases, yes. Under federal law, employers generally have the right to require employees to work overtime, provided they are compensated at the proper overtime rate, unless restricted by specific union contracts or state laws.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
      const inputs = {
        hourlyRate: document.getElementById('hourlyRate'),
        regularHours: document.getElementById('regularHours'),
        overtimeHours: document.getElementById('overtimeHours'),
        overtimeMultiplier: document.getElementById('overtimeMultiplier')
      };

      const outputs = {
        regular: document.getElementById('res-regular'),
        overtime: document.getElementById('res-overtime'),
        total: document.getElementById('res-total')
      };

      const errorDiv = document.getElementById('calc-error');

      const formatCurrency = (val) => {
        return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' }).format(val);
      };

      const calculate = () => {
        const rate = parseFloat(inputs.hourlyRate.value);
        const regHours = parseFloat(inputs.regularHours.value);
        const otHours = parseFloat(inputs.overtimeHours.value);
        const multiplier = parseFloat(inputs.overtimeMultiplier.value);

        let isValid = true;
        let errMsg = '';

        if (isNaN(rate) || rate < 0) {
          isValid = false;
          errMsg = 'Please enter a valid hourly rate greater than or equal to 0.';
        } else if (isNaN(regHours) || regHours < 0) {
          isValid = false;
          errMsg = 'Please enter valid regular hours greater than or equal to 0.';
        } else if (isNaN(otHours) || otHours < 0) {
          isValid = false;
          errMsg = 'Please enter valid overtime hours greater than or equal to 0.';
        }

        if (!isValid) {
          errorDiv.textContent = errMsg;
          errorDiv.style.display = 'block';
          outputs.regular.textContent = '$0.00';
          outputs.overtime.textContent = '$0.00';
          outputs.total.textContent = '$0.00';
          return;
        }

        errorDiv.style.display = 'none';

        const regPay = rate * regHours;
        const otPay = rate * multiplier * otHours;
        const totalPay = regPay + otPay;

        outputs.regular.textContent = formatCurrency(regPay);
        outputs.overtime.textContent = formatCurrency(otPay);
        outputs.total.textContent = formatCurrency(totalPay);
      };

      Object.values(inputs).forEach(input => {
        input.addEventListener('input', calculate);
        input.addEventListener('change', calculate);
      });

      // Initial calculation
      calculate();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .calc-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .input-group { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .input-group label { font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem; }

    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

    .error-message { background: #fee2e2; color: #b91c1c; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; border: 1px solid #f87171; }

    .results-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 5%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .highlight-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 15%, transparent); border-color: var(--accent-color); }

    .result-label { font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.5rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.5px; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .highlight-val { color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 2.5rem; }

    .explainer { margin-top: 3rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .explainer h2 { margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.8rem; }
    .explainer h3 { margin-top: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-size: 1.3rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 2rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .explainer a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; }
    .explainer a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 4rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.8rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
